{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868880/1930073101/0631.xml":{"full_text":"\u201cThe endurance of the in\nequalities of life by the poor is\nthe marvel of human society.\n\u2014James Anthony Froude.\nVol. 19\u2014No. 200.\nMILWAUKEE RANKED AS 12TH CITY\nBacks Witness on Mooney Innocence\nYOUNG PLANS\nHEARING FOR\nPARDON PLEA\nMacDonald Says\nFickert Promised\nHim Slice of Fund.\nBY GEORGE D. CRISSEY.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe United Press\nSAN FRANCISCO\u2014A special ses\nsion or the California supreme court\nto review the cases of Thomas J.\nMooney and Warren K. Billings\nneared an end Thursday with the\nrecords containing a plea for mercy\nby a man who aided in convicting\nthe pair.\nDuncan Matheson, who was cap\ntain of detectives when Billings and\nMooney were arrested in connec\ntion with the 1916 Preparedness\nday parade bombing, testified near\nthe close of the second day\u2019s session\nthat he doubted Mooney and Bil\nlings were guilty.\nEvidence Is Important.\nThe testimony of Matheson, now\ncity treasurer, was considered the\nmost important evidence presented,\novershadowing the rambling and in\ncoherent repudiation story told by\nJohn MacDonald, star witness at\nthe original trials in 1916 and 1917.\nMatheson explained that he be\nlieved Mooney and Billings guilty\nwhen he supervised the investiga\ntion prior to their trials and con\nvictions, but that subsequent de\nvelopments had caused him to\nchange his mind.\nQuestioned about MacDonald, Ma\ntheson said he had confidence in\nhim whsn he volunteered as an eye\nwitness the dynamiting, in which\n10 persons died.\nAction by Governor.\n\u201cI lost that confidence,\u201d he added,\n\u201cwhen MacDonald signed a repudia\ntion affidavit in 1921.\u201d\nPreparation for a new hearing by\nthe pardon board i\u00a3 being planned\nby Gov. C. C. Young.\nThe governor's action came while\nthe state supreme court was con\ncluding the second day of its ex\namination of MacDonald, 58-year\nold Baltimore waiter, who insists\nthat he swore falsely 14 years ago\nwhen he identified Mooney and\nWarren K. Billings as the planters\nof the Preparedness day bomb of\n1916, which killed 10 persons and\ninjured 40 others.\nYoung to Ask Questions.\nAs court recessed, Chief Justice\nWaste announced Gov. Young would\npersonally examine MacDonald\neither Saturday or Monday in con\nnection with Mooney\u2019s pardon appli\ncation. The governor said he would\nbe guided in the Mooney case by the\nsupreme court recommendation re\ngarding Billings.\nHe cannot act in the Billings\ncase without a supreme court rec\nommendation, because of a prior\nconviction of Billings.\nFickert Quizzes MacDonald.\nMacDonald was expected to be re\ncalled after the testimony of Police\nCaptain Charles Goff, whom Mac-\nDonald has accused of \u201cgoading\u201d\nhim to identify the prisoners falsely.\nMacDonald also testified that\nCharles Fickert, then district attor\nney. had influenced him to identify\nMooney and Billings.\nMacDonald, under examination by\nFickert, testified the prosecutor\npromised him a \u201cbig slice\u201d of the\n$17,500 reward if he testified as di\nrected.\nFickert declared MacDonald met\nTurn to Page 13, Column Three.\nThis and That, From\nToday\u2019s Want Ads\nA roofing salesman is wanted\nby a reliable firm.\nThree men who are repairing\nand making toys, free, for poor\nchildren desire a place to carry\non their work.\nPicnic grounds for rent.\nStr\nMilwaukee and vicinity: Fair and\nslightly warmer tontght and tomorrow.\nGentle to moderate shifting winds.\nWisconsin: Fair tonight and tomorrow.\nSlightly warmer tomorrow and in south\nwest and east-central portions tonight.\nTEMPERATURES.\n(Daylight Saving Time.)\n1 a. m 69 7 a. m 66\n2 a. m. 68 8 a. m 69\n3 a. m 67 9 a. m 73\n4 a. m 66 10 a. m 75\n5 a. rn 65 11 a. m 76\ne a. m 64 Noon 78\nHumidity: 8 p m.. 36; 8 a. m.. 59.\nTemperature 24 hours to midnight:\nMaximum. 82; minimum. 64; mean. 73;\nnormal, 71. Midnight to 10 a. m.: Max\nimum, 75; minimum, 64; relative humid\nity. 59; wind velocity at ,7 a. m., five\nmiles; direction of wind at 7 a. m.,\nnorthwest; sunrise today, 4:41; sunset,\n<;is.\nThe Milwaukee Leader\nFIRST BRITISH DIRIGIBLE IN ELEVEN YEARS REACHES AMERICA\nR-100\np X<\nF z\nWith 44 men aboard, including\nfive officers and seven passengers.\nGreat Britain\u2019s great new dirig-\nDirigible Reaches Canada;\nSpeeds on Toward Montreal\nEXPECT R-100\nAT ST. HUBERT\nABOUT 7 P. M.\nBULLETIN.\nBy The United Press.\nST. HUBERT AIRPORT \u2014A\nmessage received here from the\nR-100 at 10:10 a. m. E. S. T. said\nthe airship expected to land at 7\np. m. E. S. T.\nBY GILBERT DRAPER.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe United Press\nMONTREAL, Que.,. Canada\u2014The\ndirigible R-100 w. safe over the\nNorth American continent today\nand sped up the St. Lawrence val\nley close to its .^al at Montreal.\nThe big experimental ship, which\nGreat Britain built for rapid trans\nportation between the scattered\npar's of its empire, followed the\ncourse of the St. Lawrence river\nafter passing Belle Isle, and at\n12:25 a. m., E. S. T\u201e was a bare 750\nmiles east of its destination.\nTalks to Airport.\nThirty-five minutes later the R\n-100 sent a message to the St. Hu\nbert airport saying it was making\ngood progress and expected to ar\nrive here early Thursday evening.\nThe weather generally was most\nfavorable for this last stage of the\nmore than 3,d00-mile flight. Only a\nfew scattered clou .s dotted the\nCanadian sky, and through them the\nCanadian Pacific liner Duchess of\nYork sighted the R-100 just after\nmidnight when the steamship was\n750 miles from here.\nFour hours earlier the 1.100 had\nreached Canada, ending the most\ndifficult part of its voyage, the long\nAtlantic flight. It passed Belle Isle\nat 8:30 p. m., making good time, and\nsped on to the mouth of the St.\nLawrence for the 1 st stage of the\njourney.\nSpeeds Up Near Finish.\nThe R-100 averaged only 50 miles\nan hour between Belle sle and the\nDuchess of York with continued\ngood weather it can cru\u2019 e at an\naverage speed of 71.5 miles an hour,\nwhich would put it over the St. Hu\nbert airport before noon.\nS. Hubert airport, never before\nhost to a giant dirigible, was a hive\nof activity as its landing rew pre\npared to receive the ship.\nThe arrival of the R-100 over\nCanada was hailed here as a new\ndevelopment in aviation history.\nThe ship was designed hy Lieut.-\nTurn to Page 13. Column Thyee.\nJobless; Steals\nMail to Go to Jail\nBy Federated Press.\nCLEVELAND \u2014Because he\nwould rather be in jail than con\ntinue to tramp the streets look\ning for a job, George Kinney of\nCleveland stole a letter from the\nUnited States mails. At the of\nfice of the postoffice inspector, he\nsaid he had taken a letter from\nthe top of a mail box in an office\nbuilding, and displayed it as evi\ndence. He asked to be commit\nted to Atlanta.\n\u201cI\u2019m hungry and tired, and I\nwant a bed,\u201d he said. \u201cJune 2\nwas the last time I slept in a bed.\nSince then I\u2019ve been sleeping in\nible, the R-100, sister ship of the\nlargest air liner in the world, has\nreached Canada, the first trans-\n\u2018Keep Wages Up,\u2019 Plea\nOf Big Business Men\nNEW YORK Twelve telegrams\nfrom industrial leaders, in which\nthey view wage and salary reduc\ntions with disfavor and as tending\nto augment the economic depression,\nappeared Thursday in an article by\nRoy Dickinson, published in Print\ners\u2019 Ink.\nDickinson wrote to 25 large em\nployers to get their opinions. Of\nthe 12 thus far received, only one\nanswer even intimated wage reduc\ntions were possible.\nThe other 11 said the best way to\ndissolve the business depression is\nto maintain high wages as a means\nof providing purchasing power.\nSays Views Changing.\n\u201cTen years ago,\u201d Dickinson writes,\n.\u201cwhen I was a member of President\nHarding\u2019s unemployment conference,\nrun by Herbert Hoover, I wrote a\nminority report against wage cuts.\nI could get only one of the 50 mem\nbers to sign it\u2014-the late Samuel\nGompers. Then it was almost an\naxiom that wage cuts would bring\nback normal times.\n\u201cToday a new point of view pre\nvails. Maintaining purchasing power\nat the source is the most important\njob in the country today, for wages\nbuy more shoes and automobiles\nthan dividends.\u201d\nIn his reply J. A. Farrell, presi\ndent of the United States Steel cor\nporation, recalled the manner in\nwhich he had previously expressed\nhis opinion.\n\u201cI heard a steel man say the other\nday\u2014in fact, more than one recently\n\u2014that wages should come down,\u201d\nsaid Mr. Farrell.\nFeat Called Impossible.\n\u201cI said: \u2018Oh, no, wages in the\nsteel industry are not coming down;\nyou can make up your mind to that\n$4,000,900 IN\nTAX STILL DUE\nAlthough today is the last oppor\ntunity to pay extended taxes, there\nwas still about $4,000,000 due up to\nnoon, according to City Treasurer\nJohn I. Drew.\nAbout $500,000 of the extended\ntaxes have been paid during the last\nfew days.\nA penalty and interest will be\ncharged on all unpaid taxes after\ntoday, Drew stated.\ndoorways and alleys and wher\never I could get in from out of\nthe weather. I\u2019ve tried to find a\njob, but I can't get one. For a\nwhile I delivered bills, but there\nain\u2019t any more bills that I can\nfind to deliver.\u201d\nAsked why he didn\u2019t appeal to\nthe police for help, Kinney re\nplied wearily that that would\nhave given him only temporary\nrelief, but what he wanted was\nsomething permanent.\nIf he gets a break. Kinney will\nget a sentence of six months for\nobstructing or delaying the\nmails.\nTHURSDAY EVENING, JULY 31, 1930.\nAtlantic flight undertaken by an\nEnglish airship in 11 years.\nBound for Montreal, the great\nship left Cardington, England,\nfact If you are going out to sell\nyour goods and eliminate your\nprofit, and expect to get it out of the\nmen in the mills you are greatly\u2019\nmistaken.\u2019\nExcerpts from other replies re\nceived by Mr. Dickinson follow:\nGeorge F. Johnson, president,\nEndicott-J ohnson corporation\u2014Re\nducing. income of labor is not a rem\nedy for business depression; it is a\ndirect and contributing cause.\nR. S. Shainwald, president, Para\nfine Companies, Inc.\u2014The Paraffine\nCompanies, Inc., believes such re\nduction can and should be avoided.\nC. R. Palmer, president, Cluett,\nPeabody and Co.\u2014ln my opinion, a\ngeneral reduction of wages and sal\naries at this time is entirely unwar\nranted.\nAV. A. Sheaffer, president, W. A.\nSheaffer Pen Co.\u2014l believe it would\nbe a serious mistake to reduce\nwages.\nA. R. Erskine, president, Stude\nbaker Co.\u2014Have not even considered\nreducing wages or salaries.\nWould Retard Business.\nCharles R. Hook, president, Ameri\ncan Rolling Mill Co.\u2014Wage reduc\ntions would, in our opinion, retard\nand not stimulate business.\nA. C. Loring, president, Pillsbury\nFlour Mills Co.\u2014The new spirit in\nindustry starts a virtuous, and not a\nvicious, circle in motion.\nHoward Coonley, president, Wal\nworth Co.\u2014The Walworth Co. has\nno thought of reducing salaries or\nwages.\nHarold C. Keith, president, George\nE. Keith Co.\u2014While our company\nhas made no reduction and con\ntemplates none, yet conditions\nmight force such changes at a later\ntime.\nSPANISH DUTY\nON AUTO IS\nSHOCK TO U. S.\nMADRID American automo\nbile representatives in Madrid ex\npressed astonishment at the terms\nof the Spanish royal decree rais\ning the customs duties as pub\nlished in the Royal Gazette. They\nregarded the decree as directed\nprincipally against American auto\nbile products and as a reprisal\nagainst the American tariff.\nThe two congressmen from Mil\nwaukee, Representatives John C.\nSchafer and William H. Stafford,\nboth voted for the high tariff.\nSay Movie Extra\nAbandoned Wife\nAnd Four Children\nJoseph M. Konkel, 36 years old.\nwho has been working now and\nthen as an extra at Hollywood, was\nthe principal in\u00bba drama of his own\nmaking in municipal court today.\nKonkel is chprged with abandon\nment by his \u2019wife, Gertrude, 30\nvears old. She^said he left her and\ntheir four children in September.\n1926. The children are 5,6, 8 and\n10 years old. I\nThe court announced disposition\nof the case will be made Tuesday.\nafter numerous trial flights and\nimprovements in its construction\nsince it was completed, several\nmonths ago.\nONE DEAD, ONE\nDYING IN TONG\nDOPE WARFARE\nNEW YORK\u2014A new tong war\nover opium flared in Chinatown\nThursday.\nOne man was dead and aonther\ninjured probably fatally, and re\nports of another tong killing in Bos\nton led police to believe the hostili\nties might become country-wide.\nWednesday night Ling Nott, driv\ner for the Sun Chung Yuen Co.,\nimporters, was killed as he stood\nbehind the counter of the company\u2019s\nshot at 4 Mott st. by an assassin\nwho fired five, bullets into his body.\nAlmost simultaneously another\nvolley broke out a few doors far\nther down the street and Bock Lin\nSoo, waiting on two tourists in vhe\nshop of Kong Sun Chong, slumped\nto the floor with 10 bullets in his\nb.ody. He is not expected to live.\nOpium Shipment Involved.\nThe warfare is attributed by po\nlice, to the alleged failure of Hung\nWah Hong, slain leader of the tong\nOn group, to deliver a $140,000\nopium shipment to On Leong mem\nbers. The Hip Sings, traditional\nenemies of the On Leongs, apparent\nly are not involved in this conflict.\nHip Sing and On Leong leaders re\ncently signed a \u201cpermanent peace\npact.\u201d\nJarg Tuck was arrested and\ncharged with Ling\u2019s Murder, and\nLy Hung and Sing Say, the latter\ngiving his address as tong On head\nquarters, were held in the shooting\nof Bock.\nKilled in Theater.\nHung, the slain tong On leader,\ndied in the People\u2019s theater, on the\nBowery, during the closing scenes\nof The Robber\u2019s Mistake. He was\nasserted to have contracted with\nOn Leong members to deliver the\nopium shipment, but to have been\ndouble-crossed by smugglers whom\nhe hired to get the opium from a\nboat at sea.\nHung was unable to explain sat\nisfactorily to the On Leongs, accord\ning to the story, and was given a\nyears to make restitution. Failing\nthis, he was shot.\nFind Nine Bombs.\nNine bombs, containing nitro\nglycerine, were found in a rooming\nhouse of the Brooklyn Chinese\nquarter Thursday.\nAmong those held are Hen Yung\nIng, 33 years old, a graduate of\nNorthwestern university and a\npracticing physician.\nUPPER AVENUE\nVALUATION CUT\nAssessment of property on Wis\nconsin ave. from Twenty-eighth st.\nto Thirty-fifth st. was reduced SIOO\na foot by the board of assessors,\nTax Commissioner Louis A. Arnold\nannounced today.\nThe reduction is from SSOO to\nS4OO a foot.\nThe total reduction will be about\n$350,000.\nSales during the past two years\nhave indicated that the assessment\non this portion of the street should\nbe lowered, Arnold said.\nEntered a\u00ab second-class matter Ansrust 25. 1920, at the postoffice\nat Milwaukee, Wisconsin, under the Act of March 8. 1879.\nU. S. WILL NOT\nPLACE BAN ON\nSOVIET GOODS\nOfficial\u2019s Statement\nHeld Slap at\nLowman.\nBy Federated Press.\nWASHINGTON With protests\nagainst trade with Russia and pro\ntests against banning trade with\nRussia pouring into Washington,\nand big business and labor spokes\nmen on both sides, a high govern\nment authority stated orally that\nthe government has no intention of\ninterfering with Russian trade or\ndiscrediting Russia.\nOnly products will be barred\nwhich violate our laws against con\nvict labor or dumping, it was said,\nand these laws will be enforced\nequally to all countries.\nNewspaper men interpreted this\ndeclaration as a slap at Assistant\nSecretary of the Treasury Lowman,\nwho asserted the day before, ac\ncording to a press interview, that\nRussian sales to this country were\naimed to ruin American industry\nand that he would fight them with\nembargoes \u201cas long as the present\nfive-year industrialization program\nis in effect.\u201d\nSees \u201cEconomic Army.\u201d\nThe five-year plan, he said, cre\nated an economic army \u201cto conquer\nthe world for Bolshevism without\na shot being fired. We are facing\nwhat amounts to a declaration of\nwar.\u201d\nHe said he would use the clause\nin the Smoot-Hawley tariff bill\nbroadening the exclusion of con\nvict goods to include products of\nforced or indentured labor after\nJan. 1, 1932, to bar Russian goods.\n\u201cIf necessary,\u201d he added, \u201cwe\nwill ask congress at the December\nsession to advance the effective\ndate of the clause to 1931.\u201d This\nclause was pushed by Matthew\nIVoil, and congress held secret hear\nings on it.\nShipowners Protest Action.\nRepresentatives of owners and\ncharterers of 79 ships protested at\nthe hearing against heavy losses\ncaused by the sudden exclusion of\npulpwood and some threatened law\nsuits.\nAmong the lawyers representing\nthe shipowners was C. C. Burling\nham of one of New York\u2019s most re\nspected firms, personal friend of\nCharles E. Hughes, Elihu Root and\nother conservative Ame r i cans.\nLowman promised to issue a de\ncision within a tew days.\nAmtorg Trading corporation pro\nduced affidavits from the Amer\nican Associated Press correspond\nent and the E. M. Dutton Co., im\nporters of soviet lumber, showing\nthat convict labor is not used, and\na wire from Chairman Danishevsky\nof the lumber export organization\nstating that all operations begin\nning with logging and ending with\nloadin are performed by voluntary\npaid labor at leave to quit any\ntime.\nLowman announced he would\nconsider additional evidence from\nAmtorg at any time before or after\nhis decision.\nAmerica May Lose\nRich Export Trade\nNEW YORK If the American\ngovernment persists in stopping\nsoviet imports into the United\nStates, it will succeed in killing an\nexport business three times as\nlarge, warns Peter A. Bogdanov,\nchairman of Amtorg, American-\nRussian trading organization. \u201cIt\nis obvious,\u201d he explains, \u201cthat in\norder for the soviet union to make\nTurn to Page 13, Column One,\nSay SSOO Set as\nPrice for Wife\nFor sale, one wife, SSOO.\nThis was the offer that Joseph\nHeller, 30 years old, 565 Market\nst., made in a letter written to a\nfriend, offering his wife, Lucille,\nfor the above mentioned sum, ac\ncording to police.\nThe story was unfolded in dis\ntrict court today when Heller was\nfined sls and costs on a charge\nof disorderly conduct. Testimony\nrevealed that Heller had been\nmarried July 19. 1927, and recent\nly had been estranged from his\nwife.\nTo increase the family budget,\nHeller had given his wife S7OO to\nenable her to educate herself for\na position as bookkeeper. Since\nSeeks Tax Refund\nOn Dry Law Loss\nW||\nX 1\n$4\nZZ- 3\n3\nOne of the wealthiest women\nthe United States, Mrs. Anne\nPenfield of Philadelphia, has filed\naction in the United States court\nto recover federal tax payments\namounting to nearly $300,000 be\ncause of the losses she suffered\nwhen prohibition closed the bars\nin the hotels she owns.\nSHANGHAI HAS\nMARTIAL LAW;\nRIOTS FEARED\nSHANGHAI, China\u2014Martial law\nwas declared here for a period of\n48 hours.\nThe proclamation became effec\ntive as authorities acted to fore\nstall possible Communistic disturb\nances which they feared as a reper\ncussion of the sacking by Commu\nnists of Changsha, in Hunan prov\nince.\nFive American sailors on the gun\nboat Palos were reported wounded\nwhen Communists near Changsha\nopened fire on the vessel. The\nsailors returned the fire and the\nChinese suffered 30 casualties.\n18 Towns Captured.\nPIEPING, China \u2014Eighteen towns\nand villages in the vicinity of Lo\nyang, western Honan province, were\nin the hands of Chinese Commu\nnists and bandits Thursday, advices\nreceived here said.\nThe invaders killed hundreds of\nnatives and wounded thousands of\nothers, seizing the wealthier citi\nzens to hold for ransom.\nIt was believed all foreigners had\nescaped before the Communists ar\nrived.\nThe Communists who seized\nChangsha, capital of Hunan prov\nice, Wednesday, have issued de\nmands for $1,000,000 ransom for\nAllen Cameron and William Lingle,\nAmerican citizens, it was learned.\nThe fate of the two men was not\nknown here.\nWarning to Americans.\nWASHINGTON Americans re\nsiding in the remote Chinese prov\ninces of Hupeh, Hunan, Honan and\nKiangsi have received a second\nwarning to withdraw to places of\nsafety because of the increased ac\ntivity of Chinese bandits, the state\ndepartment has been informed.\nBritish Ship Is\nSinking, Report\nLONDON \u2014The British steamer\nNarbudda and the Spanish steamer\nLegaspi were sinking Thursday\nafter a collision 100 miles east of\nGibraltar, a Lloyd\u2019s dispatch from\nGibraltar said. Salavage steamers\nfrom Gibraltar were proceeding to\nthe two vessels\u2019 assistance.\nhis separation from his wife, Hel\nler has been demanding that she\nreturn $5 a week as payment he\nmade for her education, the judge\nwas told.\nAccording to Detectives John\nMcCarthy and Oscar Tschury,\nHeller wrote a letter about a\nmonth ago to Fred Lawson, 707\nVan Buren st., offering his wife\nfor sale.\n\u201cShe is worth more than that\nand you better snap out of it,\u201d\nthe letter read, according to the\ndetectives.\nHeller visited his wife yester\nday and after threatening her\nwith a knife, was arrested and\ncharged with diso^dely conduct.\nHOME\nEDITION\nPRICE THREE CENTS\nHOAN CHECKUP\nBEATS BUFFALO\nIN CLOSE RACE\nCity Passes Rival\u2019s\nPopulation Mark\nby 107 Persons.\nMilwaukee, with a population of\n572,324, was announced as the 12th\nlargest city in the United States,\nby the United States census bureau\nin Washington today.\nAfter a neck and neck race, Mil\nwaukee passed Buffalo, 12th in size\nin 1920, by 107 persons, according to\nthe bureau\u2019s report.\nMilwaukee\u2019s victory over its New\nYork state rival is the direct result\nof Mayor Daniel W. Hoan\u2019s activity\nin seeing that census figures were\nreported accurately from Milwaukee.\nThe police check-up ordered by\nMayor Hoan uncovered more than\n11,000 persons who declared they\nhad been omitted by the census tak\ners.\nIncrease of 25 Pct.\nMilwaukee\u2019s population indicates\nan increase of 25.3. per cent over\n1920, in contrast to the 13 per cent\nincrease in Buffalo\u2019s population and\nthe normal average increase through\nout the country of 22 per cent.\nWhen Mayor Hoan directed that\nthe police aid the census takers in\nchecking their results, those in\ncharge at first agreed. Later, how\never, they expressed resentment pt\nwhat they called \u201cpolice interfer\nence\u201d with their work.\nFind Many Omissions.\nWhen the police continued, and\nuncovered such a large number of\nomissions, the census supervisors\nstated that they could not avail\nthemselves of the additional names,\nbecause most of their folios had al\nready been sent to Washington and\nhence the new names could not be\nchecked.\nOn June 6, the mayor wrote to\nUnited States Senator Robert M.\nLa Follette, in Washington, as fol\nlows\n\u201cYou have no doubt observed in\nthe press that Milwaukee is unoffi\ncially credited by local census su\npervisors with a population oi\n068,962. This is only 3,951 fewer\nthan that of Buffalo, with a count\nof 572,913. If this slight difference\ncould be overcome, Milwaukee\nwould pass Buffalo for 12th place.\n\u201cWould Aid State.\u201d\n\u201cSuch a development would be\nquite significant. It would have\nconsiderable advertising value foi\nMilwaukee and Wisconsin, because\nin 1920'Buffalo\u2019s population exceed\ned Milwaukee\u2019s by 49,628, while in\nthe past 10 years this city has\nclimbed up with the record growth\nof 24 per cent compared with 13 per\ncent for Buffalo and a normal\naverage increase throughout the\ncountry of 22 per cent.\u201d\nThe mayor related how he con\nferred with the census supervisors\nto get them to have a recheck and\nthe police make a canvas of their\nown. The supervisors at first\nagreed, but later resented what\nthey then called \u201cpolice interfer\nence\u201d In their work. The police de\npartment, however, went ahead\nwith its work. Hoan\u2019s letter con\ntinues.\nLeft Blank Forms.\n\u201cMeanwhile the police recheck\nrevealed that a total of 11,872 per\nsons claimed they were not counted.\nThe police, to correct these dis\ncrepancies, left a regular blank\nTurn to Page 13, Column Four.\nGEHLBACH AGAIN\nLEADS IN DERBY\nLINCOLN, Neb. \u2014Lee Gehlbach\nof Little Rock, Ark., leader in the\nall-American air derby, was the\nfirst pilot to take off Thursday as\nthe fliers resumed the flight back\nto Detroit.\nGehlbach hopped off at 9:01 a.\nm., C. S. T., for Chicago, the next\novernight stop before the derby en\nries end the race at Detroit Fri\nday. The distance from Lincoln to\nChicago is 543 miles.\nPass 237th Hour Aloft.\nST. LOUIS After celebrating\nthe anniversary of their record\nflight of a year ago, Forest O\u2019Brine\nand Dale Jackson continued pilot\ning their endurance monoplane in\ncircles over Lambert municipal fly\ning field Thursday. Reporting\n\u201ceverything going fine,\u201d O\u2019Brine\nand Jackson passed their 237th\nhour aloft in their present flight\nat 4:11 a. m., C. S. T.\nNew Yorkers Still Going.\nROOSEVELT FIELD, R. L\u2014\nLouis Reichers and Robert Black\nrounded out 250 hours in the air\nat 6:34 a. m. today in their assault\non the 553-hour endurance record\nof the Hunter brothers.\nVaneev Reaches Rio.\nRIO DE JANEIRO\u2014The Amer\nican good-will flier, Capt. Lewis\nYancey, on a tour of South Amer\nica, arrived here Wednesday, con\ntinuing his hop from Buenos Aires.","height":"28449","width":"21264"}}
